        "title": "See also"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The solution minimizes the squared error"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "formulas": [
              "E = \\sum_{j=0}^k |p(x_j) - y_j|^2"
            ],
            "type": "math_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "in the equations:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "language": null,
            "text": "x[0]**n * p[0] + ... + x[0] * p[n-1] + p[n] = y[0]\nx[1]**n * p[0] + ... + x[1] * p[n-1] + p[n] = y[1]\n...\nx[k]**n * p[0] + ... + x[k] * p[n-1] + p[n] = y[k]",
            "type": "literal_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The coefficient matrix of the coefficients "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "p"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is a Vandermonde matrix."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "external_url": "",
                "href": "/docs/api/ops/polyfit",
                "kind": "link",
                "target": "polyfit",
                "text": "polyfit"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " issues a "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "~exceptions.RankWarning"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " when the least-squares fit is\nbadly conditioned. This implies that the best fit is not well-defined due\nto numerical error. The results may be improved by lowering the polynomial\ndegree or by replacing "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "x"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " by "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "x"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " - "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "x"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ".mean(). The "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "rcond"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " parameter\ncan also be set to a value smaller than its default, but the resulting\nfit may be spurious: including contributions from the small singular\nvalues can add numerical noise to the result."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Note that fitting polynomial coefficients is inherently badly conditioned\nwhen the degree of the polynomial is large or the interval of sample points\nis badly centered. The quality of the fit should always be checked in these\ncases. When polynomial fits are not satisfactory, splines may be a good\nalternative."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Notes"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
